sigul: An automated gpg signing system
https://fedorahosted.org/sigul
--

Initialization
==============

The init.py script will automatically import various keys into your database.
If the '--dev' flag is passed, it will create a 'guest' releng account for local
testing.

 $ tg-admin sql create 
 $ ./init.py
 Populating database with keys
 [1CDDBCA9] fedora-rawhide : Fedora Project automated build signing key <rawhide@redhat.com>
 [4F2A6FD2] fedora-gold : Fedora Project <fedora@redhat.com>
 [F5B783C4] signserv-test : Signing Server (Test key) <nobody@fedoraproject.org>
 [30C9ECF8] fedora-test : Fedora Project (Test Software) <rawhide@redhat.com>

Running the server
==================

 $ ./start-sigul.py

Using the client
================

 $ ./client.py
 Usage: client.py [options]

 The sigul client

 Options:
   -h, --help            show this help message and exit
   -s, --sign            Sign a list of RPMs
   -k KEY, --key=KEY     Specify a GPG key to sign with
   -c CLEAR, --clear=CLEAR
                         Make a clear text signature
   -l, --list            List available keys
   -u USERNAME, --username=USERNAME
                         Fedora username
   -v, --verbose         Show debugging messages

Using the sigul shell
=====================

Creating a new Key by hand from the sigul shell

 $ tg-admin shell
 >>> Key(key_id='1234', name='testkey', email='foo@bar.com', description='Test key')
 <Key 5 name=u'testkey' key_id=u'1234' email=u'foo@bar.com' passphrase=u'' description=u'Test key'>
